398","1311–Female":"1311–Deceased","1332–Female":"1332–Deceased","1337–1398":"1337–1398","1279–Male":"1279–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1279":"1279","1311":"1311","1332":"1332","1398":"1398","1453":"1453","1331":"1331","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Faversham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Faversham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Swale, Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and North German: nickname from Middle English <i>hert</i> (Old English <i>heorot</i>), Middle Low German <i>hërte</i>, <i>harte</i> ‘hart, stag’, perhaps for a quick-footed or timorous individual.","German: variant of   Hardt   1 and 2. It is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name or nickname from German and Yiddish <i>hart</i> ‘hard’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hartmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Erwin, Heinz, Helmut, Horst, Klaus, Manfred, Dieter, Dietrich, Franz.","North German and Danish: variant of   Hart   1.","German and Swiss German: from an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in the Netherlands, France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Czechia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Hartman  ."]},{"name":"Francoeur","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Jacques, Aime, Marcel, Normand, Alcide, Amie, Anselme, Cecile, Clemence, Dominique, Georges.","French:","soldier's name from <i>franc coeur</i> ‘sincere heart’."]},{"name":"Hartin","meanings":["Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArtáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Artán</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>Art</i>, a byname meaning ‘bear’ or ‘hero’. Compare   Hart   8.","English: habitational name from Harting (Sussex), from the Old English personal name <i>Heort</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>."]},{"name":"Hartel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Erna, Gunter, Kurt, Lutz, Otto.","German (also <b>Härtel</b>): from a pet form of an ancient Germanic compound personal name based on the element <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’.","French (Normandy): occupational name, a derivative of   Hart   7."]},{"name":"De Hart","meanings":["Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>hart</i>, modern Dutch <i>hert</i> ‘deer, hart’ or <i>hart</i> ‘heart’ (see   Hart   5), with the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’."]},{"name":"Hardt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Ernst, Erwin, Frieda, Gerhard, Gottlieb, Gunther, Hans, Heinz, Reinhold, Udo.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by woods used as pasture, from Middle High German <i>hart</i>.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic compound personal name beginning with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’."]},{"name":"Harten","meanings":["North German: patronymic from   Hart   1.","Dutch: patronymic from   Hart   4.","Dutch (<b>Van Harten</b>): habitational name from a place so named near Renkum, Gelderland."]},{"name":"Hartt","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Hart  ."]},{"name":"Harte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Sinead.","English and North German: variant of   Hart   1.","Dutch: variant of   Hart   4."]},{"name":"Hartjes","meanings":["Dutch: patronymic from a pet form of   Hart   4."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":3,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":16,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":25,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":70,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.